Scottish football|2014\u201315 season]] was [[Hamilton Academical F.C.|Hamilton Academical's]] first season in the top flight of Scottish football since [[2010\u201311 Scottish Premier League|2010-11 season]], and their first in the newly established [[2014\u201315 Scottish Premiership|Scottish Premiership]] having been promoted from the [[2013\u201314 Scottish Championship]] through the [[2013\u201314 Scottish Premiership#Final|Play-offs]]. Hamilton also competed in the [[2014\u201315 Scottish League Cup|League Cup]] and the [[2014\u201315 Scottish Cup|Scottish Cup]].\n\n==Summary==\n===Management===\nThe club began the 2014-15 season under the management of [[Alex Neil (footballer)|Alex Neil]]. On 9 January 2015, Neil left to become the new manager of, at the time, [[Football League Championship|English Championship]] side [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/30744801|title=Alex Neil: Norwich City appoint Hamilton player-manager as boss|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|work=bbc.co.uk/sport|date=9 January 2015|accessdate=22 February 2015}}</ref> [[Martin Canning]] was appointed Caretaker Player-manager, and was later on 23 January 2015 officially appointed Player-manager.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/30937644|title=Hamilton Academical: Martin Canning becomes new manager|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|work=bbc.co.uk/sport|date=23 January 2015|accessdate=22 February 2015}}</ref> With top goalscorer [[Tony Andreu]] also leaving,<ref>{{cite news|title=Transfer Deadline Day: Norwich City sign Tony Andreu|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31104649|publisher=BBC|date=4 February 2015 |accessdate=15 February 2015}}</ref> the club suffered with the sudden departures and Canning had to wait 14 matches for his first victory as manager, coming on 24 April 2015 in the [[Lanarkshire derby]] at home to [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32346135|